    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "wait sorry \"grumpy little goblin\"? lol. anyway back to the tech stuff—i checked the security groups and they seem fine. the idle timeout on the ELB is set to 60s and the app response is usually sub-500ms. \n\nif it's not the security group or a simple timeout, what else would cause an errno 104 in an AWS environment? could it be something at the OS level or the network layer?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "A \"grumpy little goblin,\" you say? Well, sometimes the best way to deal with a problem is to just acknowledge the chaos. If the security groups and the ELB timeout are clean, then we need to dig deeper into the guts of the machine, where the real mischief usually hides.\n\nAn `errno 104`—\"Connection reset by peer\"—when the application is responding quickly, points away from a simple timeout and towards something actively terminating the socket. This often means the *other* peer (the client, or perhaps an intermediary proxy) decided to just slam the door shut.\n\nAt the OS level, you're right to look there. Could it be something like an aggressive TCP stack setting on the EC2 instance itself? Sometimes, if the application is doing something heavy in the background—maybe a garbage collection cycle or a background health check that spikes CPU usage—the OS kernel might decide to drop the connection as a way to manage resources, thinking the connection is stale. It's like a clumsy, over-eager greeter who just throws the guest out because he's too busy counting his own collection of shiny pebbles.\n\nAnother network layer culprit could be an intermediate network device, though",
      "source": "target",
